Hello,

Thanks for the update.

Right so I talked with some engineers and SMEs in the background, and this kind of setup you're going for is not exactly
recommended, and not supported as well.

Assuming these were rhel-7s, the recommendation would still be to deploy and replace all rhel-7s in the topology with
rhel-8s, and only after decommissioning the rhel-7s, starting the migration to rhel-9.

Some points about this so you can have an idea:

1. RHEL 8 supports SPAKE and IdP pre-authentication, while RHEL 7 (or CentOS 7) does not, and that having RHEL 8 servers with those enabled in a RHEL (or CentOS) 7 deployment can cause problems such as users being unable to log in.
 - https://docs.redhat.com/en/documentation/red_hat_enterprise_linux/8/html/migrating_to_identity_management_on_rhel_8/migrate-7-to-8_migrating

2. In a mixed environment with RHEL 7, RHEL 8, and RHEL 9 servers, you can enforce the additional password policy settings only on servers running on RHEL 8.4 and later. If a user is logged in to an IdM client and the IdM client is communicating with an IdM server running on RHEL 8.3 or earlier, then the new password policy requirements set by the system administrator are not applied. To ensure consistent behavior, upgrade or update all servers to RHEL 8.4 and later.
 - https://docs.redhat.com/en/documentation/red_hat_enterprise_linux/9/html/managing_idm_users_groups_hosts_and_access_control_rules/defining-idm-password-policies_managing-users-groups-hosts

Beyond the above points, a myriad of risks are taken within a mixed environment such as this.

I also see there are some replication errors between your centOS 7 servers which in this case are unsupported.

Our suggestion at this point is:

1. Deploy another rhel-8, point to cpeg, and try installing the replica.
If that still fails, then share another sosreport from *both* the machines. I'll need the sosreport from cpeg as well so I can see
what cpeg (rhel-8) says during the install attempt.

But the gist of it is - having CentOS 7 + rhel-8 + rhel-9 is not 100% supported.

